[{"id":31552,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Let number of ions of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></math></p><p>Thus, as net charge has to be zero,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>83</mn><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>83</mn><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>(</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>49</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>49</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mtext>&#160;ions&#160;</mtext><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>49</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>83</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>59</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>03</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31558,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math> is body centred cubic, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p>Let mass of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;atom of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math> is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p>Edge length&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>300</mn><mi>pm</mi></math></p><p>Density&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi>cm</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi>cm</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>300</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>27</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>81</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p>Atoms of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>T</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>l</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>s</mi><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>M</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>s</mi><mi>s</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>o</mi><mi>f</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>o</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>e</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>180</mn><mrow><mn>81</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#8773;</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31574,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Ionic solid","Molecular solid","Metallic solid","Covalent solid"],"answer":3,"solution":"Covalent or network solid have very high melting point, and&nbsp;they are insulators in their solid and molten form.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31624,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$\\frac{20}{3} \\pi r^3$","$\\frac{24}{3} \\pi r^3$","$\\frac{12}{3} \\pi r^3$","$\\frac{16}{3} \\pi r^3$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} V & =n \\times\\left(\\frac{4}{3} \\pi r^3\\right) \\\\ & =4 \\times\\left(\\frac{4}{3} \\pi r^3\\right) \\\\ & =\\frac{16}{3} \\pi r^3\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":31573,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SiO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Mn</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MgO</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Mn</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> shows magnetic properties.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31616,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Covalent solid","Molecular solid","Ionic solid","Network solid"],"answer":1,"solution":"Molecular solid is the best description of water in the solid phase. For example ice is hydrogen bonded molecular solid.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":31553,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The density of the crystal can be calculated as follows,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>density</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>effective</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>number</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atoms</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>Molar</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mass</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>Avogadro</mi><mo>&#39;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>number</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>Edge</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>length</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>72</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>125</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>166</mn><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31598,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/sYcNjSfYK1vJ1-7lYeJDTT1JH6M8C78jP3vZDjUk_ik.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/m5birlhlQ_wx5d7sSq94jxZ3AwI4eADsd_RJOgxrun8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/gndji-E8KVd11Qz-gYYw1rIuA5HH8YIk6tst0WBB5Yo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Pi0VdcrPFI8O_JiVSEV-tyQRTrUZLG4EZD4CWW8LTyE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":3,"solution":"When the magnetic moments align in a regular pattern with neighbouring spins pointing in opposite directions (as in d), the substance shows antiferromagnetism.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":31621,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$30 \\%$ and $26 \\%$","$26 \\%$ and $32 \\%$","$32 \\%$ and $48 \\%$","$48 \\%$ and $26 \\%$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Packing fraction of cubic close packing and body centred packing are $0.74$ and $0.68$ respectively.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":31577,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCP</mi></math> structure : Per atom, there will be one octahedral void <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>OV</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and two tetrahedral voids <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>TV</mi><mo>)</mo></math>.</p><p>Therefore, total three voids per atom are present in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCP</mi></math> structure.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math>&nbsp;Therefore total no. of atoms of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ga</mi></math>&nbsp;will be-</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Molar</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>581</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>70</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>023</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> Now, total Number of voids <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#215;</mo></math> total no. of atoms&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>581</mn></mrow><mn>70</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>023</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>99</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>21</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>21</mn></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31564,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Number of effective atoms in HCP lattice is =6</p><p>Number of atoms of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math></p><p>Number of T.V. in h.c.p. =<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>Number</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atoms</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>Number of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math>&nbsp;atoms&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math>&nbsp;atoms.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo></math>&nbsp;of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>6</mn><mn>14</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>42</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>86</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p><p>Round off to the nearest integer = 43</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31568,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></mfenced><mtext>&#160;only&#160;</mtext></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only"],"answer":3,"solution":"(A) Crystalline solids have definite arrangement of constituent particles and have long range order.<br />(C), (D) Different constituent particles of an amorphous solid have different bond strengths and soften over a range of temperatures.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31567,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>A Frenkel defect is another form of a point defect which is created when an atom or cation leaves its original place in the lattice structure to create a vacancy while occupying another interstitial position within the solid crystal.&nbsp;Frenkel defect is dislocation defect, it is not interstitial defect, and it is not responsible for colour of solid.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31608,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$157 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$128 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$108 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$181 \\mathrm{~pm}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"For FCC,\n$r=\\frac{\\sqrt{2} a}{4}=\\frac{a}{2 \\sqrt{2}}=0.3535 a$\ngiven $a=361 \\mathrm{~pm}$\n$\\begin{aligned}\nr & =0.3535 \\times 361 \\\\\n& =128 \\mathrm{~pm}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31551,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["B and C only","B only","A and B only","A only"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Applying the electrical neutrality principle in metal deficiency defect.</p><p>One&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;is missing then two&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;ions are converted into&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;ion so&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;ion are missing and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;ion are converted in&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;ion so for each&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;ion total&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;ion&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>85</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mtext>A</mtext><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;ion is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p><p>Hence, A satisfies the condition.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31618,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$75 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$300 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$240 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$152 \\mathrm{~pm}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"For BCC, $\\sqrt{3} a=4 r$\n$r=\\frac{\\sqrt{3} \\times 351}{4}=152 \\mathrm{~pm}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (Offline)","image":null},{"id":31596,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Tridymite","Quartz","Amorphous silica","Mica"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Piezoelectric materials are those that produce an electric current when placed under mechanical stress.</p><p>Quartz is used as a piezoelectric material in electronic devices.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31548,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Bravais Lattice refers to the 14 different 3-dimensional configurations into which atoms can be arranged in crystals. The smallest group of symmetrically aligned atoms which can be repeated in an array to make up the entire crystal is called a unit cell. Crystal systems where body centred unit cell can be found are Cubic, orthorhombic and tetragonal</p><p>Hence, correct answer is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31605,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Schottky defect","Frenkel defect","Interstitial position","F-centres"],"answer":3,"solution":"The appearance of colour in alkali metal halides is generally due to F-centres. F centers in $\\mathrm{NaCl}$ produce a band of optical absorption towards the blue end of visible\nspectrum, thus the colour appears yellow under transmitted light. On the other hand, $\\mathrm{KCl}$ with $\\mathrm{F}$-centers appears magenta, and $\\mathrm{KBr}$ appears blue.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31576,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mole</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>KBr</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>119</mn><mi>gm</mi><mo>)</mo></math> have <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mn>100</mn></mfrac></math> moles <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SrBr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and hence, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup></math> moles cation vacancy (as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>Sr</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> will result <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> cation vacancy)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> Required number of cation vacancies</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>023</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup></mrow><mn>119</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>06</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>14</mn></msup><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>14</mn></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31575,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>MA</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>In HCP unit cell number of effective number of atoms is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math>,</p><p>so&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math>.</p><p>Number of tetrahedral voids</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math>&nbsp;2 x number of&nbsp;atoms forming the lattice&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mrow><mn>12</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mn>6</mn></msub></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mn>6</mn></msub></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31590,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"For ccp structure: <br/>Number of octahedral voids are <math><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math>  <br/>Number of tetrahedral voids are <math><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math>  <br/><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math> (number of atoms present in ccp structure) <br/><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>  <br/><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math>  <br/>So formula is <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><mo>.</mo></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31563,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>For&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaCl</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>58</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp;gram</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>Volume</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>43</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>58</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>58</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>43</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>23</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>23</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>08</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/df4167f2-5974-40eb-b280-47e3a0ede258-image.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 217px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mrow><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>08</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31591,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["0.027 a","0.047 a","$0.134 \\mathrm{a}$","0.067 a"],"answer":3,"solution":"For bcc\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n\\Rightarrow \\mathrm{R}=\\frac{\\sqrt{3} \\mathrm{a}}{4}\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n\\therefore \\text { Empty space at edge }=a-2 R=a-\\frac{\\sqrt{3} a}{2}\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n$=$ diameter of sphere.\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n\\therefore \\quad \\mathrm{r}_{\\text {sphere }}=\\frac{a-\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\mathrm{a}}{2}=\\left(\\frac{2-\\sqrt{3}}{4}\\right) \\mathrm{a}=0.067 \\mathrm{a}\r\n\r\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31589,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math><mn>90</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>","<math><mn>45</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>","<math><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>","<math><mn>65</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d56858d2-34ef-457b-b322-d2b27b5e8080-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 217px;\" /></p><p>If radius of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math> radius of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> will be <math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math> . Atoms in the body diagonal touch.</p><p>Therefore:<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math></p><p><math><mn>6</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math> or <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Packing Efficiency<br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>/</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>216</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>90.5</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31583,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>a</mi><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi>a</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In FCC octahedral voids are present at the edge centers and body center.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bf66da33-04ef-4ca9-9b22-754f8efdff3b-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 280px;\" /></p><p>Minimum distance between centers of two octahedral voids</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>4</mn></mfrac></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>a</mi><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31554,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>From the diagram of voids in HCP:<br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f1bac7f5-f4bd-45bc-9082-80ccb084d85b-16.PNG\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 221px;\" /><br />There are 6 octahedral voids and 12 tetrahedral voids in a HCP unit cell.<br />One unit cell of HCP contains <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>18</mn></math>&nbsp;voids</p><p>Thus, No. of voids in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mol</mi></math> of hcp</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>18</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>22</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>36</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>21</mn></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31581,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>All the corner atoms around&nbsp;body centre atom are nearest to that atom, so co-ordination number in this structure is eight.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31620,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$288 \\mathrm{pm}$","$398 \\mathrm{pm}$","$618 \\mathrm{pm}$","$144 \\mathrm{pm}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"For an ionic substance in FCC arrangement,\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& 2\\left(r^{+}+r^{-}\\right)=\\text {edge length } \\\\\n& 2\\left(110+r^{-}\\right)=508 \\\\\n& r^{-}=144 \\mathrm{pm}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":31611,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$0.56 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$0.24 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$0.96 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$0.4 \\mathrm{~nm}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"For a fcc unit cell\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& r=\\frac{\\sqrt{2} a}{4} \\\\\n& a=\\frac{4 r}{\\sqrt{2}}=2 \\sqrt{2} \\times 0.14=0.39 \\approx 0.4 \\mathrm{~nm}.\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null}]